TO AN EARLY VIOLET (Written to a Western lady-disciple from New York, 6th January 1896.)
What though thy bed be frozen earth,
Thy cloak the chilling blast;
What though no mate to cheer thy path,
Thy sky with gloom o&rsquo;ercast;
What though if love itself doth fail,
Thy fragrance strewed in vain;
What though if bad o&rsquo;er good prevail,
And vice o&rsquo;er virtue reign:
Change not thy nature, gentle bloom,
